{ <h4 data-mw-anchor="2...e6">2...e6</h4><p>With 2...e6, Black declines the Queen's Gambit in the traditional fashion. 2...e6 bolsters the d5 pawn and opens a diagonal for the development of Black's dark-squared bishop. However, 2...e6 also blocks the c8-h3 diagonal for Black's light-squared bishop. Finding a way to productively develop this piece is a perennial challenge for Black players in the QGD.</p> <h3 data-mw-anchor="Theory_table">Theory table</h3><p><b>1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6</b></p><h3 data-mw-anchor="References">References</h3><ul><li>Kasparov, Garry, &amp; Keene, Raymond 1989 <i>Batsford chess openings 2</i>. ISBN 0-8050-3409-9.</li></ul><a target="_blank" href="https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Chess_Opening_Theory/1._d4/1...d5/2._c4/2...e6">Read more on WikiBooks</a> } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 *
